            <div type="poem">
                <head type="title"><handShift new="#HANDWGC" script="print" medium="pencil"/><add place="margin-left">(1828-1829)</add><handShift new="#HANDJR1829-30" script="cursive" medium="ink"/>The ship</head>
                <lg type="stanza" rhyme="aa">
                    <!-- What to do with title "The Ship Vol I" is still undetermined: whether it a title, part of the text, heading... -->
                    <l>Look at that ship</l>
                    <l>her flying streamer and her mountain <add place="above"><space quantity="31" unit="chars"/>sides</add></l>  
                    <l>her towering mast that seems to reach <add place="above"><space quantity="29" unit="chars"/> the sky</add></l>  
                    <l>her noble stern<add place="above"><space quantity="15" unit="chars"/>&#x002A; </add> her filling sails with drops</l>
                    <l>of water hanging to her mountain bulk</l>
                    <l>glittering like<add place="above"><space quantity="16" unit="chars"/><metamark function="insertion" target="INSERTION1">&#x002A;</metamark></add> &#x0026;c</l>
                    <l>that flying streamer shows that she is <add place="below"><space quantity="26" unit="chars"/>british</add></l>
                    <l>And says though mutely I will neer <add place="above"><space quantity="26" unit="chars"/>be conquered</add></l>
                    <l>for I was by the noble british made</l>
                    <l>And Iâ€™ve a british crew . <!-- What is the function of periord to left? --> those mountain <add place="below"><space quantity="31" unit="chars"/>sides</add></l>
                    <l>below which boats do look like little pigmys</l>
                    <l>below which sloops do look like dwarfs <add place="below"><space quantity="13" unit="chars"/>below</add></l>
                    <l>which mountain sides the brigs do look <add place="above"><space quantity="30" unit="chars"/>like men</add></l>
                    <l>compared with giants .. <!-- What is the function of the two periods to left? --> those proclaim <add place="below"><space quantity="13" unit="chars"/>her trade</add></l>
                    <l>and mutely say. I am a warrior</l>
                    <l>Her towering mast <hi>that<del>is</del><add place= "above"><space quantity="24" unit="chars"></space>seems a norway pine</add></hi></l>
                    <l><hi>brought from the icy snows of Dovrefields</hi></l> <!-- these mountains are spelled both as "Dorrefield" "Dovre Field," and "Dovrefield" on the net. JR's spelling looks like Dovrefields to me -->
                    <l>when tis compared with that <add place="above"><space quantity="29" unit="chars"/>huge</add> hulk that <add place="below"><space quantity="0" unit="chars"/> <del>supports</del>bears it</add></l>
                    <l>but put it near the mast of merchant<add place="above"><space quantity="33" unit="chars"/>men</add></l>
                    <l>and it spreads to an oak of largest size</l>
                    <l>and towers in giant bulk far towards <add place="below"><space quantity="17" unit="chars"/>the clouds</add></l>             
                    <l>her stern proclaims her name the royal <add place="below"><space quantity="15" unit="chars"/>GEORGE</add></l>
                    <!-- do we want to have a crib note for 'royal George" I don't see any other ship names in the regularization/crib list. Giving it a crib note has a second problem: "royal" and George are on different 
                        lines and grouping them with a crib mote means that the crib note moves across "add" command necessary to place "George" as a continuation below. -->
                    <l>And her huge sails do bear her on her way</l>
                    <l>her faithless way that played a traitor's part</l>
                    <l>and did forsake her in the hour of need</l>
                    <l>and did precipitate her down far down</l>
                    <l>to coral banks to pearls to <name type="fictional" corresp="#NEPTUNE">Neptune</name>s court<ref type="gloss" target="the_ship_glosses.php#THESHIPROYALGEORGEGLOSS"/></l>
                    <l>those sails that sometimes pleasing zephrs <add place="below"><space quantity="16" unit="chars"/>fill</add></l>
                    <l>and sometimes <name type="fictional" corresp="#BOREAS">Boreas</name> blows with all his <add place="below"><space quantity="14" unit="chars"/>force</add></l>
                    <l>now at the present time look fair and sweet</l>
                    <l>but who can tell the future ina day</l>
                    <l>perhaps those sails are tattered rags shot through</l>
                    <l>with many a ball half dropping off their yards.</l>
                    <l>Then those destructive rows of huge machines</l>
                    <l>destructive in their making in their use</l>
                    <l><del>by which the scottish james does meet his </del> <add place="below"><space quantity="13" unit="chars"/><del>death</del></add></l>
                    <l>O war what causes thee the curse of man</l>
                    <l>tis avarice and ambition kindred vices</l>
                    <l>tis vice not war that is the curse of man</l>
                    <l>if vice were far all would be happiness <add place="below"><space quantity="19" unit="chars"/>conclusion</add></l>
                    <l>thus the whole ship united makes form</l>
                    <l>accustomed oft to battle with the storm</l>
                    <l>And urged by <name type="fictional" corresp="#BOREAS">Boreas</name> on full quick to sweep</l>
                    <l>the large and waving surface of the deep</l>
                    <l>And urged by men their whizzing balls <add place="below"><space quantity="15" unit="chars"/>to throw</add></l>
                    <l>at other men that they their deaths may <add place="above"><space quantity="35" unit="chars"/>know</add></l>
                            <addSpan xml:id="INSERTION1" spanTo="#INSERTION1-END"/><l>and her destructive rows of huge machines</l><anchor xml:id="INSERTION1-END"/>
                </lg>
            </div>          
